rComments: This was a pretty intensive class, and you really need to focus- there is required mindtap every week, but it ends up being really helpful when studying for the final. The prof is good, but he can teach a bit slowly and the material tends to be really dry. As long as you do the readings, go to tutorials, and study, you should be fine.
teacherRatingTags: ["Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Get ready to read', 'Lots of homework']

rComments: Very clear, organized lectures and slides that are easy to understand. It's definitely possible to pass the course without coming to lectures but he does add information that are not written on the slides (but shows pictures) to tests. The assignment weighting is decent as well. Overall very good prof. Recommend!

A great professor who taught the material well. His lectures were admittedly a bit boring, but that's because everything he taught was on the slides (which he would post). Tests were relatively simple, the evaluations were weighted well and he gave us plenty of opportunities to improve through the course structure. Highly recommend.
teacherRatingTags: ['Clear grading criteria', 'Get ready to read', 'Accessible outside class']

rComments: I really liked Prof. Dokshin, his lectures slides were very clear and organized and he explained concepts very clearly in lecture. He was always happy to help students with questions in class or via e-mail. The in-class activities were almost exactly like the test questions. If you go to class and do the readings, its an easy A.
lecture notes very accessible, do the reading ( 2-3 per-week) and you'll do fine. very st right forward

Professor Dokshin is a nice guy but he is usless when it comes to help. His lecture slides and organization of the lecture are nice and neat, but if you need assistance or clarification outside of the class, he is futile. When e-mailing him about concerns, he states the obvious and offers no understanding of your position.
